                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <title2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545824678]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2025-01-08T10:04:19.628-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="Research interests"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h4"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2025-02-21T15:30:06.835-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>Despite these challenges, progress in the field of neuroscience has advanced in recent years and AbbVie is leading the way. We are harnessing new tools, innovations in research methods and an enhanced understanding of biology to drive key scientific advancements and optimism for the future of neuroscience.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>To deliver the next wave of medicines in neuroscience, we’re committed to being at the forefront of science and technology. Our current research focus areas include:&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;ul>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;li>&lt;b>Investigating disease mechanisms&lt;/b> supported by human genetics, disease pathology, human induced pluripotent stem cell (iPSC) cell types and animal models with construct validity.&lt;/li>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;li>&lt;b>For proteinopathy diseases&lt;/b>, focusing on the biology of pathological proteins, mitochondrial/lysosomal dysfunction, proteostasis, neuroinflammation, neuroprotection, and neurorestoration, with the aim of preventing the spread and accelerating the clearance of toxic intracellular protein aggregates.&lt;/li>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;li>&lt;b>Exploring novel approaches&lt;/b> in addition to small molecules and biologics that offer a wide range of drug targets aimed at improving blood-brain barrier crossing and long-lasting effects – enhancing convenience and efficacy for prescribers and patients.&lt;br>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;/li>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;li>&lt;b>Optimizing clinical trial design&lt;/b> by leveraging novel technologies including machine learning and AI to accelerate the development of new therapies.&lt;/li>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;li>&lt;b>Searching for novel biomarkers&lt;/b> to measure effects of investigational drugs during clinical trials.&lt;/li>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;li>&lt;b>Using state-of-the-art technologies&lt;/b> in imaging, proteomics, single particle detection and single-cell RNAseq to advance science faster.&lt;/li>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;/ul>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>&lt;a href=&quot;/content/abbvie-com2/us/en/who-we-are/our-stories/expert-insights-the-promise-of-genetic-medicine-and-abbvies-role-in-research.html&quot;>Expert Insights: The Promise of Genetic Medicine and AbbVie’s Role in Research&lt;/a>&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container4_copy>
